<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Solidago canadensis </i>is a perennial composite with yellow flower heads that grows to 1.5 m in height. Plants create large clones from surface rhizomes (see the Hartnett and Bazzaz references). The species grows through the United States and is commonly associated with old fields in the Midwest and East (Coladonato 1993b). Morphological variation is high in the species, with five recognized subspecies. Plants in California are <i>S. canadensis </i>ssp. <i>salebrosa</i> (Pavek 2011). <br/>
<br/>
The National Vegetation Classification (NatureServe 2007a) recognized a <i>Solidago canadensis</i> alliance from the eastern United States and for California. Stands identified in the state occur in moist meadows surrounded by <i>Abies concolor </i>and <i>Abies magnifica </i>forests; the stands have similar species composition to stands of the <i>Poa pratensisâ€”Potentilla gracilis </i>association (Potter 2005). </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> A provisional <i>Solidago canadensis-Achillea millefolium</i> association identified in Yosemite National Park by Keeler-Wolf et al. (2003b) and a <i>Solidago canadensis</i> meadow type of Potter (2005) denote the alliance in the Sierra Nevada (M261Eo). We need additional sampling to resolve relationships between this and other wet-montane meadow alliances in the state, and elsewhere with in the range of the species. </div>
</div>

	

    
